 Which six dhammas are very helpful
Six conditions conducive to amiability
There is the case friends where a monk is set on bodily acts of goodwill with regard to his companions in the holy life to their faces  behind their backs This is a condition that is conducive to amiability that engenders feelings of endearment engenders feelings of respect leading to a sense of fellowship a lack of disputes harmony  a state of unity
And further the monk is set on verbal acts of goodwill with regard to his companions in the holy life to their faces  behind their backs This too is a condition that is conducive to amiability that engenders feelings of endearment engenders feelings of respect leading to a sense of fellowship a lack of disputes harmony  a state of unity
And further the monk is set on mental acts of goodwill with regard to his companions in the holy life to their faces  behind their backs This too is a condition that is conducive to amiability that engenders feelings of endearment engenders feelings of respect leading to a sense of fellowship a lack of disputes harmony  a state of unity
And further whatever righteous gains the monk may obtain in a righteous wayeven if only the alms in his bowlhe does not consume them alone He consumes them after sharing them in common with his virtuous companions in the holy life This too is a condition that is conducive to amiability that engenders feelings of endearment engenders feelings of respect leading to a sense of fellowship a lack of disputes harmony  a state of unity
And furtherwith reference to the virtues that are untorn unbroken unspotted unsplattered liberating praised by the observant ungrasped at leading to concentrationthe monk dwells with his virtue in tune with that of his companions in the holy life to their faces  behind their backs This too is a condition that is conducive to amiability that engenders feelings of endearment engenders feelings of respect leading to a sense of fellowship a lack of disputes harmony  a state of unity
And furtherwith reference to the view that is noble leading outward that leads those who act in accordance with it to the right ending of suffering  stressthe monk dwells with his view in tune with that of his companions in the holy life to their faces  behind their backs This too is a condition that is conducive to amiability that engenders feelings of endearment engenders feelings of respect leading to a sense of fellowship a lack of disputes harmony  a state of unity
